post_text: Students in Mrs. Hayward and Ms. McBrayer’s class had a very special virtual visit from a guest speaker, Amanda Buffington, who works for Delta Airlines. On September 11, 2001, Ms. Buffington was supposed to be on United Flight 175. She got sick the day before and had to drop the flight scheduled for September 11th. Amanda shared with the class her accounts of 9-11 as a flight attendant and the days that followed as she flew into NYC on September 14th on the Mercy Flight. We are so thankful that Ms. Buffington took time out of her busy job as a Regional Manager - Crew Resources Flight Attendant Scheduling for Delta Airlines to speak to our classes.

On September 11, 2001, Ms. Buffington was supposed to be on United Flight 175. She got sick the day before and had to drop the flight scheduled for September 11th. Amanda shared with the class her accounts of 9-11 as a flight attendant and the days that followed as she flew into NYC on September 14th on the Mercy Flight. We are so thankful that Ms. Buffington took time out of her busy job as a Regional Manager - Crew Resources Flight Attendant Scheduling for Delta Airlines to speak to our classes.

post_text:
Congratulations to the CES Teacher of the Year, Jennifer Holley!

Calhoun Elementary School is excited to announce that Jennifer Holley has been selected as the 2021-2022 Teacher of the Year. Mrs. Holley is currently in her 8th year of teaching. She began her teaching career in Cobb County and came to Calhoun Elementary in 2015. She currently teaches 4th grade math at CES. Jennifer holds a math and a gifted endorsement. Mrs. Holley is a team player and can always be counted on to offer help and support to her colleagues and students. Mrs. Holley greets her students with a smile each morning and her colleagues describe her as a natural motivator. She is married to Brock Holley and they have one daughter, Julia. One of her peers stated, “Jenn goes above and beyond for her students, parents, and fellow teachers! She takes initiative and heads up difficult tasks.”

Our Teachers of the Year are sponsored by First Bank of Calhoun and we appreciate their support as we recognize our outstanding teachers!

To support Georgia's public schools, fill out your 2020 Census!

We need a complete count in the Census to ensure full funding for programs like the National School Lunch program, IDEA special education funding, and Title I grants -- and right now, Georgia is lagging behind other states for response rate.

To fill out your Census, visit my2020census.gov or call 844-330-2020 (English) or 844-468-2020 (Español). If you have received a paper form, you can complete and mail it at any time.

The CMS Boys and Girls Golf Teams continued their undefeated seasons Tuesday at Fields Ferry Golf Course. The boys defeated Red Bud, Cass & Rockmart. Kole Offutt led the Jackets with his low medalist round of 44. Jace Johns had the runner-up medalist round of 46. Zach Mallandine and Christian Ruddell had the other counting scores of 53.

The CMS Girls Golf Team was also victorious in the Tri-Match as Tyler Robinson led the Lady Jackets with her low medalist round of 61. Annie Eickman tied for runner-up medalist on the day with her score of 62. Ella Offutt had the other runner-up medalist round of 62 for the Phoenix.

WELLNESS WEDNESDAY TIP | Sponsored by Vargo Orthodontics

DOES "EARLY SCREENING" MEAN EARLY TREATMENT?
Only a few orthodontic problems need correction at an early age, but the 7 yr. old screening is important in the event that a problem is detected. In most cases, your child's growth and development will be monitored (free of charge) every 6 months for the doctor to determine when and if the time is right. Our "Growth & Development" program helps Dr. Vargo stay on top of any problems that might occur.

SHOULDN'T I WAIT UNTIL MY CHILD HAS LOST OFF OF HIS or HER BABY TEETH FOR A SCREENING?
Actually, waiting until all of the permanent teeth have come in, or until facial growth is nearly complete, makes correction of some problems more difficult. Some corrections cannot be accomplished once the face and jaw are no longer growing. We want to create a healthy environment for the permanent teeth that are trying to come in! So early screening is very important!

Vargo Orthodontics
Office: 706.290.0011
Location: 419 East 2ND Avenue, Rome, GA 30161
www.vargosmile.com

post_text: Proud of CHS graduate Claudia Langford Brown, She is serving as Program Scientist for Climate Change and Health at the CDC. #lifelonglearner #pursuitofexcellence
shared_text:
Jim Langford
September 6 at 9:08 AM ·

My daughter, Claudia Langford Brown, broadcasting live from her home this morning on the Weather Channel. She’ll be on again live at 10:20am EDT this morning (Sunday). She’s the CDC Program Scientist for Climate Change and Health at the CDC. She’s talking about the new CDC website that allows the public to track climate events that can be harmful to health. This is particularity important for vulnerable populations. So proud of her and her work. Hard to believe she’s been at the CDC for seven years.

post_text:
Both boys & girls CMS golf teams won Wednesday at the Elks Golf Club. The boys defeated the Phoenix by 30 strokes and Ashworth by 37 strokes. Kole Offutt, eighth grader, led the Jackets Golf team by shooting a low medalist round of 42 on 9-holes. Other counting scorers with runner-up medalist rounds of 45 for the Jackets were eighth graders, Jace Johns and Christian Ruddell. Zach Mallindine, seventh grader, also scored a 45. Other competing Varsity Jackets were Peyton Joy and Max O'Daniel. Charlie Boyd had the low round of 50 for the Phoenix.

The Lady Jacket Golfers defeated Ashworth and Red Bud on Wednesday at the Elks Golf Club. Tyler Robinson, seventh grader, led the ladies with her low medalist score of 56 for the match. Following closely behind Tyler was Annie Eickman with the other counting score and runner-up medalist round of 57 for the Lady Jackets. Ella Offutt had the low round for the Lady Phoenix with her round of 58.

Both boys & girls CMS golf teams began their seasons in victorious fashion Tuesday at Fields Ferry golf club. In boys action the Jackets defeated the Phoenix by 22 strokes. Eighth grader Kole Offutt led the Jackets golf team by shooting 46 over the 9-holes at Fields Ferry golf course. Other counting scorers for the Jackets were 8th graders Jace Johns, with a fine round of 49, Christian Ruddell with a 53 and 7th grader Zach Mallindine with a 54. Peyton Joy and Max O'Daniel also competed for the varsity Jackets.

The Lady Jacket golfers were also victorious winning a close match with Red Bud. Seventh grader Tyler Robinson led the ladies with a low medalist score for the match and Annie Eickman had the other counting score for the Lady Jackets. Ella Offutt from Red Bud also tied for low medalist honors on the day.

The presenter will be Kasey Farriba, a Certified Professional Resume Writer and owner of hireguide, a Resume & Career Coaching Business.

The event is free to students who present a valid student identification card and $50 for adult professionals. You may register online at http://www.gordoncountychamber.com/events/details/resume-workshop-sponsored-by-coca-cola-bottling-company-3337. Due to COVID-19 and social distancing rules, space will be limited, so sign up fast!

Participants are encouraged to bring their personal laptops. All attendees are advised to bring their own PPE.

post_text: Welcome New Staff!
shared_text:
Calhoun Schools
August 4 at 9:48 PM ·

Calhoun City Schools welcomed all of its new teachers and staff during New Teacher Orientation on Monday, August 3, 2020 and Tuesday, August 4th. Seventeen new staff members were introduced which included many familiar faces, former Calhoun High School graduates, former employees, employee's spouses, and those new to the area. New staff included: CJ Collins, Chandler Curtis, Cassey Gerry, Luke Green, Nic Hann, Kent Howard, Kate Johnson, Thomas Lester, Daniel McArthur, Thomas Osborne, Elizabeth Painter, Shae Pharr, Amy Scoggins, Jennifer Smith, Yenis Solis, Heather West, and Tess Wright. We are looking forward to a great year with this exceptional team of new employees.

We're looking forward to graduating our seniors at Hal Lamb Field in Phil Reeve Stadium this evening.

GRADUATION LIVE STREAM |

This year's commencement ceremonies will be a ticketed event held on Saturday, August 1st beginning at 8pm at Hal Lamb Field in Phil Reeve Stadium. Guests of all ages require a ticket to enter the stadium. In the event of inclement weather, we will move to the CHS gymnasium on Saturday evening.

For those who are not able to attend the event, the ceremony will be live streamed at www.calhounyellowjackets.com

post_text: As we prepare to recognize the many accomplishments of the Class of 2020, the CHS Class of 1969 wishes to honor a most deserving senior with a $500 scholarship. Class member Dianne Kirby was on hand today at graduation practice to surprise Mikail Lawrence with the scholarship announcement. Mikail plans to attend Jacksonville State University to study nursing. “Our class is proud to support Mikail as she prepares to go to college. We wish her much success,” stated Kirby.

JOB POSTING | Middle Grades English Language Arts Teacher / ESOl Sheltered Model

Calhoun Middle School uses a Shelter Content delivery model to provide EL students ESOL services. EL students receive language assistance and ELA content instruction in a class. This delivery model requires a teacher to be certified in Middle Grades - Language Arts and the ESOL endorsement or ESOL certification.

Certification Required: Middle Grades Language Arts and ESOL endorsement / certification
Certified Salary Schedule
10 month employee

To apply, please complete an application at https://www.applitrack.com/calhounschools/onlineapp/.

Calhoun Primary and Elementary are excited to welcome students back on August 12th. Parents will be receiving phone calls from their child’s teacher on July 23 and July 28 from 8:00 am - 4:00 pm. Teachers will be calling individual families to introduce themselves, welcome them, and discuss pertinent information regarding the beginning of the school year. We eagerly anticipate our students returning and are excited to see everyone!

En La Escuela Primaria y Elemental de Calhoun están entusiasmados de darles la bienvenida a los estudiantes el 12 de Agosto . Los padres recibirán llamadas telefónicas del maestro de sus hijos(as) el 23 y 28 de Julio de 8:00 a.m. a 4:00 p.m. Los maestros llamarán a familias individualmente para presentarse, darles la bienvenida y discutir la información pertinente sobre el comienzo del año escolar. ¡Esperamos ansiosamente el regreso de nuestros estudiantes y estamos emocionados de verlos a todos!

Attention Student Drivers: Student Parking Registration begins this week. All parking registration for the 2020-21 school year will take place online. Please follow the schedule for your assigned registration date. If you miss your date this week, you may register any day after your assigned date. Students and parents are able to verify student's cumulative GPA via Parent Portal. Please make sure to follow all steps listed on the CHS Parking Information webpage(https://www.calhounschools.org/high/students/parking-information). https://www.calhounschools.org/high/students/parking-information

Monday: Seniors with a 93+ Cumulative GPA

Tuesday: All Seniors

Wednesday: Juniors with a 93+ Cumulative GPA

Thursday: All Juniors

Friday: Sophomores with a 93+ Cumulative GPA

Saturday: All Sophomores

Please call the high school main office with any questions. Thank you.

shared_text:
Georgia Department of Education
June 23 at 7:41 PM ·

Governor Kemp announced today that the Georgia Broadband Deployment Initiative (GBDI) is launching the Speedtest by Ookla® pilot project statewide through August. This project is designed to equip school leaders with the clearest picture possible of internet connectivity for Georgia’s students and teachers for the upcoming school year.

Georgians are encouraged to download the free Ookla Speedtest app (Android or iOS-Apple) to the various devices that they use to connect to the internet (smartphones, tablets, laptops, and desktop computers) and take several tests in the places where connectivity is important to them. The easy-to-use Speedtest, along with the information available at the Broadband Initiative website, will assist school leaders as they plan for their digital learning strategies.

Click here for more information: https://gov.georgia.gov/press-releases/2020-06-23/state-launches-internet-speedtest-pilot-schools

Calhoun City Schools has amended the FY21 Budget Planning Calendar to include the following Budget Work Sessions and Hearings:

Friday, July 10th - 10AM - Noon: Budget Work Session
Friday, July 24th - Noon: First Budget Hearing (Adopt Tentative Budget)
Monday, July 27th - Noon: Regular Monthly Board Meeting (Adopt August Spending Resolution and Second Budget Hearing)
Monday, August 10th - 6:00 p.m.: Called Board Meeting (Adoption of Final Budget by Board)

All meetings will be held at the Board of Education Office Building at 334 South Wall Street.

The Final FY21 Budget will be presented to the Mayor and City Council following the Adoption from the Board of Education on Monday, August 10, 2020 at 7:00 p.m. at the August City Council Meeting at the Calhoun Depot.

Calhoun Community Education
June 29 at 1:09 PM ·

Campers had a great time at Jacket Jamboree last week! They enjoyed visiting with Angie Gravitt as she shared her talents, ideas and recipes. Mrs. Gravitt allowed campers to pick blueberries, squash, zucchini, banana peppers and tomatoes from the school garden. After picking everything from the garden they learned how to make “salad on a stick”. To wrap up the week, campers made homemade zucchini bread with Mrs.Gravitt. She talked to campers about kitchen safety, recipes, dry ingredients, wet ingredients, mixing and cleaning up. Mrs. Gravitt really showed our campers how to make vegetables fun and yummy!

Calhoun Junior Jacket Academy is currently accepting applications for the 2020-21 school year. The Junior Jacket Academy and Calhoun Pre-K will be transitioning to Calhoun Primary School while an exciting new early learning center is being built at the current JJA/ Pre K location. Due to limited space and to ensure the safety of our youngest students, CCS will be offering one 3 and 4 year old class for the 2020-2021 school year.

Applications can be downloaded at https://www.calhounschools.org/pre-k-and-jr-jacket-academy/junior-jacket-academy or can be picked up at Calhoun Primary/PreK at 102 Raymond King Dr., Calhoun, GA. 30701. Completed applications with all required documents should be returned to 102 Raymond King Dr. by July 31st, 2020. Questions? Call 706-602-6603.

Attention all female athletes interested in playing volleyball at Calhoun High School:

If you plan to tryout for volleyball for the 2020-2021 season, you need to complete the registration process in the Calhoun High Volleyball Google Classroom. The classroom code is 3f2ntci.

Once you join classroom, you need to complete two forms: Tryout Registration Form and Summer Questionnaire. These forms are located under the "Classwork" tab. Both forms MUST be completed by Wednesday, June 3rd.
Summer workouts will begin on Tuesday, June 9th. You must be registered in order to attend workouts.

After registering, you can sign up for the Volleyball Remind. Text @20chsvb to 81010. If you have any questions, please email Coach Hann at hannn@ccsjackets.org.

shared_text:
Georgia Department of Education
June 1 at 10:45 AM ·

With the Georgia Department of Public Health, we are releasing guidance for a safe return to in-person instruction in fall 2020.

The guidelines are intended to ensure the safety of students, staff, and families while remaining flexible, responsive, and achievable in the K-12 setting. They are guidelines, not mandates, and are adaptive to multiple scenarios. School districts should review the guidance in consultation with their local public health departments and choose which methods to adopt.

Georgia's K-12 Restart Working Groups will meet through the summer and fall to build out resources for school district planning and implementation.

Learn more here: https://www.gadoe.org/External-Affairs-and-Policy/communications/Pages/PressReleaseDetails.aspx?PressView=default&pid=776

We’ve also added senior photos from Calhoun, Gordon Central, and Sonoraville to create a 200-page salute to these special young people from the Class of 2020. post_text:
REMINDER | Calhoun City Schools became a “Charter” school system in 2010. One of the major pillars of the charter is the “governance” component. Under the charter, each school must form a “School Governance Team” (SGT). Please notify your school’s principal (in writing) by noon Friday, May 15, 2020 if you are interested in running for election to the SGT.

School Governance Team Parent Elections
Elections for the following vacant SGT Positions:

Calhoun PreK - 1 (Upcoming) PreK Parent Representative Seat

Calhoun Primary School - 2 (Upcoming) Kindergarten Parent Representative Seats

Calhoun Elementary School - 2 Parent Representative Seats

Calhoun Middle School - 1 Parent Representative Seat

will be held on

Friday, May 22, 2020 - 7:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. at the Board of Education Office at 334 South Wall Street

Voting should take just a few minutes so stop by before work, during your lunch break or after work to vote for your school’s parent representative.

Thank you for your support as we continue to make Calhoun schools the best schools in the nation.

Go Jackets!

Congratulations to these awesome students who placed at the State Skills USA competition:

Nicholas McGill - 1st place Action Skills (demonstration of patdown and handcuffing)
Banks Hathcox - 3rd place Cabinetmaking
Wesley Hathcox - 2nd place Construction Math

Jaden Brock - 1st place Tile (2 time State Champion in Tile, which is CHS history for back to back Tile State Championship at SkillsUSA.)

Attention Calhoun Primary & Elementary Student Parents:

For Complex we will take in chrome books, iPads, library books, classroom reading materials, money owed, completed work packets, etc. and give out awards, contents from student desks, medication/epi pens housed in clinic, report cards on May 19th and 22nd. We are not expecting our yearbooks to be in by that time as they are delayed. We will distribute those at the beginning on next school year. Location and times are as followed:

May 19th 10:00 am-6:00 pm
K-1 Primary car rider lane
2-3 Carpool lane (back of the campus in bus loading area)
4-5 Elementary car rider lane

May 22nd 7:00 am-3:00 pm
K-1 Primary car rider lane
2-3 Carpool lane (back of the campus in bus loading area)
4-5 Elementary car rider lane

We ask that everyone stay in the car and a school representative will take in and give out items from the curb to promote social distancing.

A Message from the Superintendent:

It’s National Teacher Appreciation Week and National Small Business Week! Our teachers are out of this world and we’ve launched the week with some special treats to support our local businesses and to show our appreciation to such an awesome staff! Teachers and staff will be able to enjoy blizzards from DQ, coffee from Calhoun Coffee Company and donuts from Daddy O’s. Thank you to these partners in education for your help to recognize our teachers and staff this week. May the “fourth” be with all of you! Have an awesome week! Go Jackets! 💛🖤🐝
